<font color="#FF0000">CAMARADERIA &amp; STATS</font><br>
<tt>Sun Jan 19  8:43:31 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
While I heartily endorse what Fez said, I have to say that Doc Del was right about the lack of camaraderie, at least as far as my unit was concerned.  Oh, we got along all right, but I didn't experience that brotherly sort of feeling I had always thought existed in combat units.  I suspect that is at least partly my fault, because I was pretty selfish at that time of my life.  I also suspect that it had something to do with the fact that we were all &quot;replacements&quot; - we didn't go over as a unit, fight as a unit, and leave as a unit.  And partly it was the nature of my unit (radio platoon in H.&amp; S. Co.) - we'd get &quot;farmed out&quot; to line companies and then rotated back to battalion c.p., or we'd be with the command group on operations; each of us with our  own unique experience.  I'd be interested to hear other stories along this line - what was the situation like for you.<br><br>
I have contact with only 1 guy who was in my platoon in 'Nam now, though there's a couple of others I wouldn't mind seeing (and a couple that I never want to see again!).<br><br>
As to the statistics on suicide, I must admit that my initial reaction is (&quot;Well, it's the CDC - OF COURSE they're going to find lower numbers - they're the government and they've got a vested interest in down-playing this.&quot; &quot;Aren't they the ones that said Agent Orange didn't have a significant impact on health?&quot;) etc., etc.  This despite the fact that I am a scientist (biologist) and I'm trained to &quot;be objective&quot; (I can't do that when it come to 'Nam - sorry 'bout that).  Anyway, thanks for the source - I meant to look up Marilyn Young's source for her numbers but I haven't got around to it yet.  Maybe next post...<br><br>
In the meantime, I hope lots of vets write in and post their experience of camaraderie - like Doc Del I'd like to believe my experience was atypical.
<p><code>-- miketol@mtco.com  (Mike Toliver) </code><p>


